TY  - JOUR
AU  - Ahern, Kenneth R.
AU  - Duchin, Ran
AU  - Shumway, Tyler
T1  - Peer Effects in Risk Aversion and Trust
PY  - 2014
Y1  - 2014/11/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhu042
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 27
IS  - 11
SP  - 3213
EP  - 3240
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - Existing evidence shows that risk aversion and trust are largely determined by environmental factors. We test whether one such factor is peer influence. Using random assignment of MBA students to peer groups and predetermined survey responses of economic attitudes, we find causal evidence of positive peer effects in risk aversion and no effects in trust. After the first year of the MBA program, the difference between an individual and her peers' average risk aversion has shrunk by 41%. Finding no peer effects in trust is consistent with recent research showing that distinct cognitive processes govern risk aversion and trust.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhu042
ER  - 



